  "companies": [],
  "statement": "# Redundant Connection\n\nA tree had one extra undirected edge added. Return the last edge that creates a cycle.\n\n## Examples\n\n**Example 1**\n\n```text\nInput: edges = [[1,2],[1,3],[2,3]]\nOutput: [2,3]\n```\n\n**Example 2**\n\n```text\nInput: edges = [[1,2],[2,3],[3,4],[1,4],[1,5]]\nOutput: [1,4]\n```\n\n**Example 3**\n\n```text\nInput: edges = [[1,2],[2,3],[1,3]]\nOutput: [1,3]\n```\n\n## Constraints\n\n- Inputs are sized for local offline execution.\n- Return values follow the method description.",
  "editorial": "Use the graph structure directly: traverse reachable states, maintain visited or distance state, and update the answer when each node or cell is settled.",
  "solution_notes": "```python\nclass Solution:\n    def findRedundantConnection(self, edges):\n        parent = list(range(len(edges) + 1))\n        def find(x):\n            while parent[x] != x:\n                parent[x] = parent[parent[x]]; x = parent[x]\n            return x\n        for a, b in edges:\n            ra, rb = find(a), find(b)\n            if ra == rb: return [a, b]\n            parent[ra] = rb\n```",
  "hints": [
    "Model the state explicitly.",
    "Prefer linear or near-linear graph traversal when possible."
  ],
  "starter_code": {
    "python": "class Solution:\n    def findRedundantConnection(self, edges):\n        pass\n"
  },
